    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Profit Margin Calculator</h2>
      <p>
        This profit margin calculator provides instant insight into your business profitability. Enter your total revenue, the amount you received from sales, and your total cost, the amount you spent to generate that revenue. The calculator instantly displays your profit margin as a percentage and your net profit in dollars. These figures update in real time as you type, letting you quickly model different pricing and cost scenarios.
      </p>
      <p>
        Understanding your profit margin is essential for making informed business decisions. It tells you how many cents of profit you keep from every dollar of revenue. A margin of 30% means you keep $0.30 in profit for every $1.00 in sales. Tracking this metric over time helps you identify trends, evaluate pricing strategies, and benchmark against competitors in your industry.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>The Profit Margin Formula</h2>
      <p>
        The profit margin formula is straightforward: <strong>Profit Margin (%) = ((Revenue - Cost) / Revenue) &times; 100</strong>. First, subtract your total cost from total revenue to find the net profit. Then divide the net profit by revenue and multiply by 100 to express it as a percentage. This formula works for individual products, product lines, or an entire business.
      </p>

      <h3>Gross Margin vs. Net Margin</h3>
      <p>
        Gross profit margin uses only the cost of goods sold (COGS) and measures production efficiency. Net profit margin includes all expenses: COGS, operating costs, interest, taxes, and overhead. Gross margin helps evaluate pricing and sourcing decisions, while net margin reveals overall business health. Most publicly traded companies report both. A healthy gross margin with a poor net margin suggests operational inefficiencies or excessive overhead.
      </p>

      <h3>Improving Your Profit Margin</h3>
      <p>
        There are two fundamental ways to improve profit margin: increase revenue or reduce costs. On the revenue side, consider raising prices, upselling premium products, or improving sales conversion rates. On the cost side, negotiate better supplier terms, reduce waste, automate repetitive tasks, or eliminate underperforming product lines. Even small improvements in margin can have an outsized impact on total profit when applied across high volumes of sales.
      </p>

      <h3>Industry Benchmarks</h3>
      <p>
        Profit margins vary dramatically across industries. Technology and software companies often enjoy margins of 20-40% due to low marginal costs. Retail businesses typically operate on thin margins of 2-5%, relying on high volume for profitability. Restaurants average 3-9%, while financial services companies often achieve 15-25%. Comparing your margin against industry averages gives you a realistic assessment of your competitive position.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How do you calculate profit margin?</h3>
      <p>
        Profit margin is calculated by subtracting total cost from revenue to get profit, then dividing profit by revenue and multiplying by 100. The formula is: Profit Margin (%) = ((Revenue - Cost) / Revenue) x 100. For example, if revenue is $200 and cost is $150, the margin is ((200 - 150) / 200) x 100 = 25%.
      </p>

      <h3>What is the difference between profit margin and markup?</h3>
      <p>
        Profit margin is profit divided by revenue (selling price), while markup is profit divided by cost. If you buy something for $60 and sell it for $100, the profit is $40. The margin is 40/100 = 40%, but the markup is 40/60 = 66.7%. Margin is always lower than markup for the same transaction.
      </p>

      <h3>What is a good profit margin for a business?</h3>
      <p>
        Good profit margins vary widely by industry. Net profit margins of 10-20% are generally considered healthy for most businesses. Software companies often achieve 20-40%, retail typically sees 2-5%, while restaurants average 3-9%. Compare your margin to industry benchmarks for a meaningful assessment.
      </p>

      <h3>What is the difference between gross and net profit margin?</h3>
      <p>
        Gross profit margin only subtracts the direct cost of goods sold (COGS) from revenue. Net profit margin subtracts all expenses including COGS, operating costs, taxes, and interest. Net margin gives a more complete picture of profitability, while gross margin shows how efficiently you produce or source your products.
      </p>

      <h3>Can profit margin be negative?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes, a negative profit margin means expenses exceed revenue, resulting in a loss. This is common for startups investing heavily in growth, or during periods of unexpected cost increases. Sustained negative margins require funding from savings, loans, or investors to keep the business operating.
      </p>
    

